# Rules for TypeScript

## Basic

- Reuse existing utilities, composables, and components; avoid duplication.
- Import explicitly (no Nuxt auto-imports for project code). `imports.scan: false` keeps Vue runtime APIs (`ref`, `computed`, `watch`, etc.) and compiler macros (`defineProps`, `defineEmits`, `withDefaults`, etc.) auto-imported
- Prefer function declarations for named exported functions and use arrow functions for callbacks/inline handlers
- Prefer `interface` for extendable object contracts
- Use `as` (type assertion) only when necessary (DOM narrowing, branding, literals)
- Put `as const` on constant objects / arrays
- Use `satisfies` for constant objects / arrays that must conform to a specific type but also need precise literal types

## Code Style and Structure

- Extract helpers to stay DRY and keep modules focused

## Nuxt

- **Computed must be pure**: no side effects, mutations, API calls, or I/O
- Use `shallowRef` by default; use `ref` only when you need deep reactivity (e.g. nested property updates without replacing `.value`).
- Use VueUse composables for reactivity/performance
- Call `navigateTo({ ... })` instead of string paths
